\title{"develop Web Game"}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Use when Codex is building or iterating on a web game (HTML/JS) and needs a reliable development + testing loop: implement small changes, run a Playwright-based test script with short input bursts and intentional pauses, inspect screenshots/text, and review console errors with render_game_to_text."}

\subtree{
\title{Develop Web Game}
\p{Build games in small steps and validate every change. Treat each iteration as: implement → act → pause → observe → adjust.}

\subtree{
\title{Skill paths (set once)}
\pre{\startverb
export CODEX_HOME="${CODEX_HOME:-$HOME/.codex}"
export WEB_GAME_CLIENT="$CODEX_HOME/skills/develop-web-game/scripts/web_game_playwright_client.js"
export WEB_GAME_ACTIONS="$CODEX_HOME/skills/develop-web-game/references/action_payloads.json"
\stopverb}

\p{User-scoped skills install under \code{\startverb $CODEX_HOME/skills\stopverb} (default: \code{\startverb ~/.codex/skills\stopverb}).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Pick a goal.} Define a single feature or behavior to implement.}
\li{\strong{Implement small.} Make the smallest change that moves the game forward.}
\li{\strong{Ensure integration points.} Provide a single canvas and \code{\startverb window.render_game_to_text\stopverb} so the test loop can read state.}
\li{\strong{Add \code{\startverb window.advanceTime(ms)\stopverb}.} Strongly prefer a deterministic step hook so the Playwright script can advance frames reliably; without it, automated tests can be flaky.}
\li{\strong{Initialize progress.md.} If \code{\startverb progress.md\stopverb} exists, read it first and confirm the original user prompt is recorded at the top (prefix with \code{\startverb Original prompt:\stopverb}). Also note any TODOs and suggestions left by the previous agent. If missing, create it and write \code{\startverb Original prompt: <prompt>\stopverb} at the top before appending updates.}
\li{\strong{Verify Playwright availability.} Ensure \code{\startverb playwright\stopverb} is available (local dependency or global install). If unsure, check \code{\startverb npx\stopverb} first.}
\li{\strong{Run the Playwright test script.} You must run \code{\startverb $WEB_GAME_CLIENT\stopverb} after each meaningful change; do not invent a new client unless required.}
\li{\strong{Use the payload reference.} Base actions on \code{\startverb $WEB_GAME_ACTIONS\stopverb} to avoid guessing keys.}
\li{\strong{Inspect state.} Capture screenshots and text state after each burst.}
\li{\strong{Inspect screenshots.} Open the latest screenshot, verify expected visuals, fix any issues, and rerun the script. Repeat until correct.}
\li{\strong{Verify controls and state (multi-step focus).} Exhaustively exercise all important interactions. For each, think through the full multi-step sequence it implies (cause → intermediate states → outcome) and verify the entire chain works end-to-end. Confirm \code{\startverb render_game_to_text\stopverb} reflects the same state shown on screen. If anything is off, fix and rerun.}
\li{\strong{Check errors.} Review console errors and fix the first new issue before continuing.}
\li{\strong{Reset between scenarios.} Avoid cross-test state when validating distinct features.}
\li{\strong{Iterate with small deltas.} Change one variable at a time (frames, inputs, timing, positions), then repeat steps 7–13 until stable.}
}

\p{Example command (actions required):}

\pre{\startverb
node "$WEB_GAME_CLIENT" --url http://localhost:5173 --actions-file "$WEB_GAME_ACTIONS" --click-selector "#start-btn" --iterations 3 --pause-ms 250
\stopverb}

\p{Example actions (inline JSON):}

\pre{\startverb
{
  "steps": [
    { "buttons": ["left_mouse_button"], "frames": 2, "mouse_x": 120, "mouse_y": 80 },
    { "buttons": [], "frames": 6 },
    { "buttons": ["right"], "frames": 8 },
    { "buttons": ["space"], "frames": 4 }
  ]
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Test Checklist}
\p{Test any new features added for the request and any areas your logic changes could affect. Identify issues, fix them, and re-run the tests to confirm they’re resolved.}

\p{Examples of things to test:}

\ul{
\li{Primary movement/interaction inputs (e.g., move, jump, shoot, confirm/select).}
\li{Win/lose or success/fail transitions.}
\li{Score/health/resource changes.}
\li{Boundary conditions (collisions, walls, screen edges).}
\li{Menu/pause/start flow if present.}
\li{Any special actions tied to the request (powerups, combos, abilities, puzzles, timers).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Test Artifacts to Review}
\ul{
\li{Latest screenshots from the Playwright run.}
\li{Latest \code{\startverb render_game_to_text\stopverb} JSON output.}
\li{Console error logs (fix the first new error before continuing).}
}

\p{You must actually open and visually inspect the latest screenshots after running the Playwright script, not just generate them. Ensure everything that should be visible on screen is actually visible. Go beyond the start screen and capture gameplay screenshots that cover all newly added features. Treat the screenshots as the source of truth; if something is missing, it is missing in the build. If you suspect a headless/WebGL capture issue, rerun the Playwright script in headed mode and re-check. Fix and rerun in a tight loop until the screenshots and text state look correct. Once fixes are verified, re-test all important interactions and controls, confirm they work, and ensure your changes did not introduce regressions. If they did, fix them and rerun everything in a loop until interactions, text state, and controls all work as expected. Be exhaustive in testing controls; broken games are not acceptable.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Game Guidelines}
\subtree{
\title{Canvas + Layout}
\ul{
\li{Prefer a single canvas centered in the window.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Visuals}
\ul{
\li{Keep on-screen text minimal; show controls on a start/menu screen rather than overlaying them during play.}
\li{Avoid overly dark scenes unless the design calls for it. Make key elements easy to see.}
\li{Draw the background on the canvas itself instead of relying on CSS backgrounds.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Text State Output (render_game_to_text)}
\p{Expose a \code{\startverb window.render_game_to_text\stopverb} function that returns a concise JSON string representing the current game state. The text should include enough information to play the game without visuals.}

\p{Minimal pattern:}

\pre{\startverb
function renderGameToText() {
  const payload = {
    mode: state.mode,
    player: { x: state.player.x, y: state.player.y, r: state.player.r },
    entities: state.entities.map((e) => ({ x: e.x, y: e.y, r: e.r })),
    score: state.score,
  };
  return JSON.stringify(payload);
}
window.render_game_to_text = renderGameToText;
\stopverb}

\p{Keep the payload succinct and biased toward on-screen/interactive elements. Prefer current, visible entities over full history. Include a clear coordinate system note (origin and axis directions), and encode all player-relevant state: player position/velocity, active obstacles/enemies, collectibles, timers/cooldowns, score, and any mode/state flags needed to make correct decisions. Avoid large histories; only include what's currently relevant and visible.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Time Stepping Hook}
\p{Provide a deterministic time-stepping hook so the Playwright client can advance the game in controlled increments. Expose \code{\startverb window.advanceTime(ms)\stopverb} (or a thin wrapper that forwards to your game update loop) and have the game loop use it when present. The Playwright test script uses this hook to step frames deterministically during automated testing.}

\p{Minimal pattern:}

\pre{\startverb
window.advanceTime = (ms) => {
  const steps = Math.max(1, Math.round(ms / (1000 / 60)));
  for (let i = 0; i < steps; i++) update(1 / 60);
  render();
};
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Fullscreen Toggle}
\ul{
\li{Use a single key (prefer \code{\startverb f\stopverb}) to toggle fullscreen on/off.}
\li{Allow \code{\startverb Esc\stopverb} to exit fullscreen.}
\li{When fullscreen toggles, resize the canvas/rendering so visuals and input mapping stay correct.}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Progress Tracking}
\p{Create a \code{\startverb progress.md\stopverb} file if it doesn't exist, and append TODOs, notes, gotchas, and loose ends as you go so another agent can pick up seamlessly. If a \code{\startverb progress.md\stopverb} file already exists, read it first, including the original user prompt at the top (you may be continuing another agent's work). Do not overwrite the original prompt; preserve it. Update \code{\startverb progress.md\stopverb} after each meaningful chunk of work (feature added, bug found, test run, or decision made). At the end of your work, leave TODOs and suggestions for the next agent in \code{\startverb progress.md\stopverb}.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Playwright Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Prefer a local \code{\startverb playwright\stopverb} dependency if the project already has it.}
\li{If unsure whether Playwright is available, check for \code{\startverb npx\stopverb}:}
\li{If \code{\startverb npx\stopverb} is missing, install Node/npm and then install Playwright globally:}
\li{Do not switch to \code{\startverb @playwright/test\stopverb} unless explicitly asked; stick to the client script.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Scripts}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb $WEB_GAME_CLIENT\stopverb} (installed default: \code{\startverb $CODEX_HOME/skills/develop-web-game/scripts/web_game_playwright_client.js\stopverb}) — Playwright-based action loop with virtual-time stepping, screenshot capture, and console error buffering. You must pass an action burst via \code{\startverb --actions-file\stopverb}, \code{\startverb --actions-json\stopverb}, or \code{\startverb --click\stopverb}.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{References}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb $WEB_GAME_ACTIONS\stopverb} (installed default: \code{\startverb $CODEX_HOME/skills/develop-web-game/references/action_payloads.json\stopverb}) — example action payloads (keyboard + mouse, per-frame capture). Use these to build your burst.}
}
}
}